<doc id="1192013" wikidata="Q2669907" url="?curid=1192013" title="Whitehead manifold">
<text>In mathematics, the Whitehead manifold is an open 3-manifold that is contractible, but not homeomorphic to formula_1 discovered this puzzling object while he was trying to prove the Poincaré conjecture, correcting an error in an earlier paper where he incorrectly claimed that no such manifold exists.

A contractible manifold is one that can continuously be shrunk to a point inside the manifold itself. For example, an open ball is a contractible manifold. All manifolds homeomorphic to the ball are contractible, too. One can ask whether &quot;all&quot; contractible manifolds are homeomorphic to a ball. For dimensions 1 and 2, the answer is classical and it is &quot;yes&quot;. In dimension 2, it follows, for example, from the Riemann mapping theorem. Dimension 3 presents the first counterexample: the Whitehead manifold.

==Construction==
Take a copy of formula_2 the three-dimensional sphere. Now find a compact unknotted solid torus formula_3 inside the sphere. (A solid torus is an ordinary three-dimensional doughnut, that is, a filled-in torus, which is topologically the product of a circle and a disk.) The closed complement of the solid torus inside formula_4 is another solid torus.
Now take a second solid torus formula_5 inside formula_3 so that formula_5 and a tubular neighborhood of the meridian curve of formula_3 is a thickened Whitehead link.

Note that formula_5 is null-homotopic in the complement of the meridian of formula_10 This can be seen by considering formula_4 as formula_12 and the meridian curve as the &quot;z&quot;-axis together with formula_13 The torus formula_5 has zero winding number around the &quot;z&quot;-axis. Thus the necessary null-homotopy follows. Since the Whitehead link is symmetric, that is, a homeomorphism of the 3-sphere switches components, it is also true that the meridian of formula_3 is also null-homotopic in the complement of formula_16

Now embed formula_17 inside formula_5 in the same way as formula_5 lies inside formula_20 and so on; to infinity. Define &quot;W&quot;, the Whitehead continuum, to be formula_21 or more precisely the intersection of all the formula_22 for formula_23

The Whitehead manifold is defined as formula_24 which is a non-compact manifold without boundary. It follows from our previous observation, the Hurewicz theorem, and Whitehead&#x27;s theorem on homotopy equivalence, that &quot;X&quot; is contractible. In fact, a closer analysis involving a result of Morton Brown shows that formula_25 However, &quot;X&quot; is not homeomorphic to formula_1 The reason is that it is not simply connected at infinity.

The one point compactification of &quot;X&quot; is the space formula_27 (with &quot;W&quot; crunched to a point). It is not a manifold. However, formula_28 is homeomorphic to formula_29

David Gabai showed that &quot;X&quot; is the union of two copies of formula_30 whose intersection is also homeomorphic to formula_1

==Related spaces==
More examples of open, contractible 3-manifolds may be constructed by proceeding in similar fashion and picking different embeddings of formula_32 in formula_33 in the iterative process. Each embedding should be an unknotted solid torus in the 3-sphere. The essential properties are that the meridian of formula_33 should be null-homotopic in the complement of formula_35 and in addition the longitude of formula_32 should not be null-homotopic in formula_37

Another variation is to pick several subtori at each stage instead of just one. The cones over some of these continua appear as the complements of Casson handles in a 4-ball.

The dogbone space is not a manifold but its product with formula_38 is homeomorphic to formula_29

